                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Alfred H. Love &#38; Co.<lb/>
                No. 219 Chestnut Street.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; 1 Mo. 29 1894<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais<lb/>
                546 N 6th St<lb/>
                Respected Friend&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I was deeply touched to<lb/> read in the Ledger the report of the<lb/> beautiful &#38; appropriate prayer you<lb/> offd last Saty in behalf of George W<lb/> Childs.  I could not content myself<lb/> to enjoy it alone&#44; so I called my<lb/> family together &#38; read it for the second<lb/> time.  It shows me what a true<lb/> &#38; good heart you have &#38; how near we<lb/> are toether in all those things which<lb/> make peace possible.  I thank you<lb/> sincerely.  You see Mr childs named<lb/> my cousin Emma Peterson.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have often thought it would be<lb/> pleasant all round for our Peace<lb/> Socy to meet in your Synagogue<lb/>  We would suggest some Sunday<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>afternoon or evng&#44; as the fires<lb/> would not be out&#44; or any other<lb/> time&#44; if you preferred Saty eveng<lb/> all right.  Suppose you see if<lb/> it could be brought round &#38; then<lb/> you speak &#38; any of our other good<lb/> Hebrew friends you might mention<lb/> or find willing to speak.<lb/></p>
            <p>We would find 200 there of<lb/> our socy.  All necessary expenses<lb/> we would pay.<lb/></p>
            <p>I do feel as if I wanted to see<lb/> more of you for you do represent<lb/> such a beautiful pacific spirit.<lb/>  Your assured friend<lb/> Alfred H Love<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
